Pulling data from Twitter API

  • I use rtweet
    • Returns tibble with 83 columns
    • Works well with tidyverse & tidytext
library(rtweet)

access_token <- ''
access_secret <- ''
consumer_key <- ''
consumer_secret <- ''

create_token(
  app = '',
  consumer_key = consumer_key,
  consumer_secret = consumer_secret,
  access_token = access_token,
  access_secret = access_secret
)


Rtweet has the get_timeline function that retrieves a user’s tweets. It has two primary arguments: the user name and the number of tweets to return.

Caution Twitter has rate limits. If you ask for too much data too quickly it will time you out, meaning you will have to wait (usually about an hour). You can also be blacklisted for spamming or hammering the server. Please see the Twitter API for more information.

alfa <- get_timeline('', n = 25) # user handle in the quotes


There is quite a lot of really useful information returned in tibble format.

#Grabbing network data using Tidytext

  • REGEX objects for use in tidytext
  • Pulled directly from Text Mining with R by Julia Silge and David Robinson
  • These make it easy to pull out the @ symbol names and removes hyperlinks, etc.
regex <- "@([A-Za-z]+[A-Za-z0-9_]+)(?![A-Za-z0-9_]*\\.)"

replace_reg1 <- 'https://t.co/[A-Za-z\\d]+|'

replace_reg2 <- 'http://[A-Za-z\\d]+|&amp;|&lt;|&gt|RT|https'

replace_reg <- paste0(replace_reg1, replace_reg2)

unnest_reg <-  "([^A-Za-z\\d#@']|'(?![A-Za-z_\\d#@]))"


I’ve created a function - by chaining together dplyr code - that pulls the data I’m interested in. Mostly, I am interested in users who tweet at other users as if they are having a conversation, specifically if it is reciprocated or not.

pull_mentions <- function(x = tibble) {
  x %>%
    filter(!str_detect(text, '^RT')) %>%
    mutate(text = str_replace_all(text, replace_reg, ''),
           row.id = row_number()) %>%
    unnest_tokens(word,
                  text,
                  token = 'regex',
                  pattern = unnest_reg,
                  collapse = F) %>%
    mutate(mentioned = ifelse(str_detect(word, '@'), word, NA)) %>%
    distinct(mentioned) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    pull(mentioned)
}



mentions <- pull_mentions(alfa)


- The pull_mentions function allows us to make a 1-degree network the users I, @elliot_meador, have tweeted at over the last 25 tweets.

We can then loop through each of my 1-degree mentiones (people I tweet at) and pull their timelines using map_df from purrr and the code above.

foxtrot <- map_df(mentions, function(x) { #map_df merges the dataframes
  get_timeline(x, n = 25)
  
})


Now we can easily combine all the Twitter data into one dataframe.


The dataframes returned from rtweet contain list columns of things like geo-coordinates and hashtags. This is useful information that we want to keep. So, it’s best to simplify it and then change it into a character vector before tokenising.

golf <- echo %>%
  mutate_if(is.list, simplify_all) %>%   # take all lists and simplify
  as_tibble()  %>%
  mutate_if(is.list, as.character) %>%   # change all lists to a character
  filter(!str_detect(text  , '^RT')) %>% # this is the same as above
  mutate(text = str_replace_all(text  , replace_reg, ''),
         row.id = row_number()) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word,
                text,
                token = 'regex',
                pattern = unnest_reg,
                collapse = F) %>%
  mutate(mentioned = ifelse(str_detect(word, '@'), word, NA))


The dataframe golf contains our network identifiers as well as the tweet text data in a tidy format. We can now do our network analysis and sentiment analysis in using this dataframe. We use graph_from_data_frame from igraph. The simplify function removes self-loops.

library(RColorBrewer)
Spectral_n <- colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(11, 'Spectral'))

tweet_g <- golf %>% 
  transmute(screen_name = str_to_lower(str_c('@', screen_name)),
            mentioned) %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  graph_from_data_frame() %>% # from igraph
  simplify()
  
  
  
plot(tweet_g, vertex.label = NA)


Plotting the network in a meaningful way

Igraph can plot the network using the plot function, but the base plot can be difficult to read and make sense of, especially if the network is big and complicated.

We need to add some graph ‘attributes’ to decorate the plot and pull something more meaningful from it.

The following block of code uses dplyr joins to combine data back and forth until we get a series of color vectors that correspond to the nodes and the edges.

The idea is make the color radiate out from the centre node - which will usually be the first twitter user pulled - out through the network. This way, the reader’s eye can more easily discern the direction of tweets within the network. 

library(scales)

tweet_edges <- tweet_g %>%
  as_data_frame() %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  mutate_all(funs(str_trim(.)))




edge_col <- tweet_edges %>%
  mutate(betweenness = edge.betweenness(tweet_g)) %>%
  arrange(betweenness) %>%
  distinct(from) %>%
  mutate(color = sample(Spectral_n(nrow(.)))) %>%
  right_join(tweet_edges) %>%
  select(name = from, to, color)



tweet_nodes <- tweet_g %>%
  as_data_frame(., 'vertices') %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  mutate_all(funs(str_trim(.)))



node_col_temp <- tweet_nodes %>%
  mutate(in.degree = degree(tweet_g, mode = 'in')) %>%
  left_join(edge_col) %>%
  select(-to) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  filter(is.na(color)) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  filter(in.degree == 1) %>%
  pull(name)


node_add <- edge_col %>%
  filter(to %in% node_col_temp) %>%
  select(name = to, color.2 = color)



n_shared_node <- tweet_nodes %>%
  left_join(edge_col) %>%
  select(-to) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  left_join(node_add) %>%
  mutate_all(funs(ifelse(is.na(.), '', .))) %>%
  unite(color, color, color.2, sep = '') %>%
  filter(color == '') %>%
  nrow()

node_col <- tweet_nodes %>%
  left_join(edge_col) %>%
  select(-to) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  left_join(node_add) %>%
  mutate_all(funs(ifelse(is.na(.), '', .))) %>%
  unite(color, color, color.2, sep = '') %>%
  mutate(color = ifelse(color == '', Spectral_n(n_shared_node), color))
  
edge.cols.ad <- map2(edge_col$color,
                     rescale(edge.betweenness(tweet_g), 0.5, 1),     
                     function(x, y) {
                       adjustcolor(x, y)
                     }) %>% 
                     flatten_chr()



node.cols.ad <- map2(node_col$color, 
                     rescale(degree(tweet_g), 0.5, 1), 
                     function(x, y){
                        adjustcolor(x, y)
                     }) %>% 
                     flatten_chr()


Let’s put this into the plot using the base R function.

par(mar = c(0,0,0,0), bg = 'black')
plot(
  tweet_g,
  vertex.label = NA,
  vertex.color =node.cols.ad,
  vertex.frame.color = node.cols.ad,
  vertex.size = rescale(degree(tweet_g),c(2,10)),
  edge.color = edge.cols.ad,
  edge.arrow.size = .25, 
  edge.width = 1.5,
  asp = 1)


GGraph

There is a relatively new package ggraph that works very well of ggplot2 and it uses similar syntax. Let’s try to reproduce the plot from above using ggraph.

library(ggraph)

tweet_g %>% 
 ggraph() +
 geom_edge_fan(aes(alpha = ..index..,
                   color = as.factor(1:ecount(tweet_g))), 
                   show.legend = F)+
 geom_node_point(color = node.cols.ad, 
                 size = rescale(degree(tweet_g),c(1, 3)),
                 show.legend = F)+
 scale_edge_color_manual(values = edge.cols.ad) +
 coord_equal()+
  theme_graph(
    foreground = 'white',
    background = 'black',
    title_colour = 'white',
    subtitle_colour = 'white',
    caption_colour = 'white'
  ) +
  labs(title = 'Online Networks',
       subtitle = 'Data from Twitter API',
       caption = 'Nodes are size by number of\ntimes they are mentioned in tweets (in-degree)')


Discussions and Sentiment analysis

We can easily look at what people are talking about because we are using a tidy approach.

golf %>%                              # our dataframe from earlier
  anti_join(stop_words) %>%           # stop words are not interesting to us, 'to', 'a'
  select(screen_name, word) %>% 
  count(word, sort = T) %>%           # then just count the words and make a plot
  head(10) %>% 
  mutate(word  = fct_reorder(word, n)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(word, n))+
  geom_col()+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title = 'Elliot\'s top words in his two-degree ego network')
## Joining, by = "word"
